fields.description:
The attached Python SOAP client essentially does:

token = soap.login(jirauser, passwd)
soap.getAllPermissions(token)

This breaks with a cryptic XML parse error:

unknown>:1:497: duplicate attribute

Further investigation reveals that JIRA is generating invalid XML in response to the SOAP query (see attached response.xml).  The problem is the duplicated xsi:type attribute, which is duplicated (not allowed in XML):

<getAllPermissionsReturn  soapenc:arrayType="ns2:RemotePermission[20]" xsi:type="soapenc:Array" xsi:type="soapenc:Array" ...

fields.description:
*Rationale*
Python is a very popular language and it is expected that Bamboo treats it like a first class citizen, similar to the JDK. The current workaround is to manually configure executables.

*Steps*

* Install and Configure Bamboo
* Install Windows Server 2012 R2 (win-agent-01)
* Install and configure an Bamboo Agent on win-agent-01
* Install Python 3.4 and Python 2.7
* Visit the Bamboo website, select the agent and view its capabilities.

Note than even through Python was installed on the agent, Bamboo does not detect it. 

*Expected*
Since Python 2.x is different than Python 3.x and there are some compatibility issues, it is expected that Bamboo will detect Python as follows:

* *Python 2.7* - C:\Python27\pyhton.exe
* *Python 2.4* - C:\Python34\pyhton.exe

It is possible to install Python in other file paths.  The expectation is that Bamboo will detect python when installed on linux agents too.

fields.description:
C:\svnrepo\hooks>C:\Bamboo-2.5.5-std\scripts\svn-triggers\postCommitBuildTrigger.py http://localhost:8085 STACK-LOCAL
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "C:\Bamboo-2.5.5-std\scripts\svn-triggers\postCommitBuildTrigger.py", line 12, in <module>
    fileHandle = urllib2.urlopen(remoteCall)
NameError: name 'urllib2' is not defined


For python 3.0 it should be
{code}
#!/usr/bin/python
#
# ./postCommitBuildTrigger.py http://bamoo.atlassian.com/bamboo/ myBuildName

import sys
import urllib.request;

baseUrl = sys.argv[1]
buildKey = sys.argv[2]

remoteCall = baseUrl + "/api/rest/updateAndBuild.action?buildKey=" + buildKey
fileHandle = urllib.request.urlopen(remoteCall)
fileHandle.close()
{code}

fields.description:
I really like a lot Bamboo, I used it several years with J2EE development. Now that I have switched to growing and exciting Django + Phython world, I found of course few support behind it.

I have found some bits and pieces at:
   http://reinout.vanrees.org/weblog/2011/06/07/bitbucket.html
   http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1419629/atlassian-bamboo-with-django-python-possible
   http://forums.atlassian.com/thread.jspa?threadID=45982
   https://answers.atlassian.com/questions/35809/how-to-parse-django-tests-with-bamboo


Things that I imagine for nice Django + Python support would be:
# main Know-how / guide page for Django + Python under Bamboo
# Test results integration and recommended test frameworks.
# pep8 integration  (http://pypi.python.org/pypi/pep8)
# pyflakes integration  (https://launchpad.net/pyflakes)
# PyLint integration (http://pypi.python.org/pypi/pylint)
# Nice Reporting integration from all those valuable 3rd party.


If this feature would be added, it will immediately mean a "BUY" decision for my company.  In the meantime I have good old Jenkins.

I also think there are quite a lot of projects/companies for such nice feature.

fields.description: The hg_local script uses "/usr/bin/env python" to run python. This causes problems if the default version of python is python 3.x (mercurial doesn't work with py3k). I think that GUI apps ignored the $PATH setting of the user in OS X 10.8, but in OS X 10.9, it seems to use my $PATH and picks /opt/local/bin/python, which is a symlink to python3.3. Just hard-coding python2.7 might be an acceptable solution, but with a bit of extra code you could set it up so that python2.7 is only used as a fallback if python corresponds to python3.

fields.description:
I was trying to use both XML-RPC and SOAP with Confluence 2.2.5 from Python. XML-RPC works fine, except for not handling UTF-8 communication well. The content you get from the Confluence server is OK, but if you put the same thing back the Unicode characters will be damaged.

I am aware that XML-RPC has limitations with respect to such encodings, so I wanted to try my luck with the SOAP interface. It works for some function calls but for others it fails with the following 'duplicate' attribute error:
(There was a similar issue for Jira a year ago, related to the Apache Axis version used).

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "iso.py", line 27, in ?
    pages = soap.getPages(auth, "QMS")
  File "/var/lib/python-support/python2.4/SOAPpy/Client.py", line 421, in __call__
    return self.__r_call(*args, **kw)
  File "/var/lib/python-support/python2.4/SOAPpy/Client.py", line 443, in __r_call
    self.__hd, self.__ma)
  File "/var/lib/python-support/python2.4/SOAPpy/Client.py", line 347, in __call
    p, attrs = parseSOAPRPC(r, attrs = 1)
  File "/var/lib/python-support/python2.4/SOAPpy/Parser.py", line 1006, in parseSOAPRPC
    t = _parseSOAP(xml_str, rules = rules)
  File "/var/lib/python-support/python2.4/SOAPpy/Parser.py", line 988, in _parseSOAP
    raise e
xml.sax._exceptions.SAXParseException: <unknown>:1:474: duplicate attribute

---

The example code:

import SOAPpy, getpass, datetime

soap = SOAPpy.WSDL.Proxy('https://wiki.iblsoft.com/rpc/soap-axis/confluenceservice-v1?wsdl')

fields.description:
Looking at the JIRA Python API code, it appears that if I call jira.search_issues with expand='renderedFields', it should return a renderedFields object, similar to the fields object, but with fields such as "description" converted from wiki markup to HTML.

Examining issue.raw, I see that renderedFields is empty.  This appears to be a bug, unless I'm not understanding how to make this work properly.

Note that I can work around this by retrieving the issue key in my query result and then using jira.issue(key, expand='renderedFields').  So there's a reasonable work-around, but it would be nice if jira.search_issues handled this without the extra step.

fields.description:
The following error occurred while trying to set up a remote hg repository on a fresh fecru-2.9.2 installation on FreeBSD:
{code}
2013-02-09 17:45:25,045 INFO  [InitialPinger1 ring-mvc-lastmod-bug] fisheye BaseRepositoryScanner-ping - [spring-mvc-lastmod-bug] starting initial scan of repository 
2013-02-09 17:45:25,060 INFO  [InitialPinger1 ] fisheye OneOffPingRequest-doRequest - Exception during FishEye Incremental Indexing of spring-mvc-lastmod-bug: Unable to clone remote repository: ssh://example.com/hg/projects/spring-mvc-lastmod-bug
{code}

I believe that the problem is that fecru is not forwarding its PATH environment variable when invoking hg. If hg is compiled such that the first line of its python source is using "!#/usr/bin/env python" (as a hg installed with "make local" would be), then it fails.

For reference, here is some output from "truss -eafp <fecru-java-pid>" showing that the only environment variable provided to hg is HGENCODING.
{code}
3066: chdir("/home/ecd/fecru-2.9.2/var/cache/spring-mvc-lastmod-bug/clone") = 0 (0x0)
3066: fcntl(3,F_SETFD,FD_CLOEXEC)               = 0 (0x0)
1941: _umtx_op(0x800648128,0xf,0x0,0x0,0x7ffffeff1b00,0x0) ERR#60 'Operation timed out'
1941: _umtx_op(0x800648608,0xf,0x0,0x0,0x7ffffbbbd860,0x0) ERR#60 'Operation timed out'
1941: read(528,0x7ffff9a72dec,4)                = 0 (0x0)
3066: execve("/home/ecd/bin/hg", [ "hg", "--config", "ui.verbose=false", "pull", "ssh://example.com/hg/projects/spring-mvc-lastmod-bug" ], [ "HGENCODING=US-ASCII" ]) = 0 (0x0)
3066: mmap(0x0,32768,PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANON,-1,0x0) = 34366128128 (0x800618000)
1941: close(521)        3066: issetugid(0x800818a60,0x7fffffffefcf,0x40,0x0,0xffff800800819a91,0x0) = 0 (0x0)
{code}

items.fromString:
The following error occurred while trying to set up a remote hg repository on a fresh fecru-2.9.2 installation on FreeBSD with OpenJDK 1.7.0_011:
{code}
2013-02-09 17:45:25,045 INFO  [InitialPinger1 ring-mvc-lastmod-bug] fisheye BaseRepositoryScanner-ping - [spring-mvc-lastmod-bug] starting initial scan of repository 
2013-02-09 17:45:25,060 INFO  [InitialPinger1 ] fisheye OneOffPingRequest-doRequest - Exception during FishEye Incremental Indexing of spring-mvc-lastmod-bug: Unable to clone remote repository: ssh://example.com/hg/projects/spring-mvc-lastmod-bug
{code}

My guess was that piece of code was assuming python is located at "/usr/bin/python" (as it would be for most linux distributions). Mine is located at "/usr/local/bin/python" (and yes, my PATH includes this).

I put a symbolic link from /usr/local/bin/python to /usr/bin/python and found that it now works. This, however, is more of a hack/workaround.

2013-02-09 17:45:25,060 INFO  [InitialPinger1 ] fisheye OneOffPingRequest-doRequest - Exception during FishEye Incremental Indexing of spring-mvc-lastmod-bug: Unable to clone remote repository: ssh://example.com/hg/projects/spring-mvc-lastmod-bug
{code}

My guess is that something is assuming python is located at "/usr/bin/python" (as it would be for most Linux distributions). Mine is located at "/usr/local/bin/python" (and yes, my PATH includes this).

I put a symbolic link from /usr/local/bin/python to /usr/bin/python and found that it now works. This, however, is more of a hack/workaround.

Version information:
{code}
[ecd@qk ~]$ pkg_version -v | grep -e ^openjdk -e python
openjdk-7.11.21_1                   =   up-to-date with port
python27-2.7.3_6                    =   up-to-date with port
{code}

I have done no configuration on my crucible installation besides unzipping it and going through the initial setup on the web interface.

The following error occurred while trying to set up a remote hg repository on a fresh fecru-2.9.2 installation on FreeBSD:

fields.description:
(Background, I opened a support issue and was asked to open a ticket instead https://support.atlassian.com/servicedesk/customer/portal/23/JST-151976)

I am trying to setup a CI job for a Python project which depends on numpy.

In our plan, we ensure each build does a clean checkout. It then goes on to install requirements via pip.

Since numpy takes considerable amount of time to install when using pip (~5m on m3.medium because the package is downloaded as source and is recompiled each time), too speed up the CI cycle, we decided to have it preinstall by using yum install during the startup script.

Subsequently, the plan will continue and install the remaining dependencies – which includes numpy. Typically in most Fedora/CentOS/RHEL bases systems, pip will see the system package present and will not reinstall it again.

However, in this case, something is wrong and numpy is reinstall again by pip.

This significantly affects our CI turnaround time as the build only takes 6 mins, with 5 min being spent installing numpy!

fields.description:
Our OSQA modifications may / may not be causing issues, but in an effort to keep our modifications self-contained and "keep an upgrade path," we need to move our Atlassian development within OSQA  into a self-contained "atlassian" module.  API development (REST API, ANSWERS-34) needs to be put in its own module anyway, so making the first step there seems like a proper step toward setting up the right framework.  

Similarly, as we need a way to package/auto-install our modifications for proper deployment ( https://extranet.atlassian.com/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=1892778156 ),  having a self-contained atlassian module with patches to related files in OSQA's core (including a python script to diff/merge those changes) would remove the manual parts of deploying Answers.

Details:
 * Customizations of Python and any other ancillary resources required by OSQA/Answers need to be put in a subfolder of the top-level folder called "atlassian" in the OSQA folder.
 * Any customizations that absolutely cannot be done without modifying OSQA core files (like removing URLs and such) need to be fully recorded in the "Customizations" page ( here: https://extranet.atlassian.com/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=1892778156 ) or need to be added to a "CUSTOMIZATIONS" file in related folders.
 * Create a "atlassian_setup.py" script to automate patching of relevant files and modify standard OSQA Database (for things such as Profile Pictures, which adds columns / modifies the schema).
 * Package the whole thing together and release X.Y.Z versions where X is relative to OSQA releases, Y is our Answers incarnation (new features, etc), and Z is our bugfix release.

fields.description:
Hi team,
I referred to http://docs.atlassian.com/fisheye-crucible/latest/wadl/crucible.html but found no possibility to get reviews in specified time frame, like "get all closed reviews from 2011-10-01 to 2011-11-01". As from your support reply there is no such possibility, but it will be great help for all API automation work.

Best Regards, Pavel

eg PageId = 21168377 gives that error but PageID =115309 works fine
